Nov 21 2009 	First and Last time staying at Caesars	My husband and I go to Vegas every fall. We had never stayed at Caesars, so we figured we would give it a try. We were in the Palace Tower. The room was clean and very nice, but the only view we had was of another building. We didn't have a room service menu in the room, so I called down and they said they would send one right up. Well, we never did get our menu! The ice machine on our floor and also on 2 other floors would not work and we called the front desk twice about this before it was fixed. The coke machine also didn't work on 3 different floors that we tried and they took our money. The buffett is way overpriced for what they offer. The breakfast buffett was good, but not worth the price. Expect to put on your walking shoes because it takes forever to get anywhere in the hotel, especially from your room to the casino. This was also one of the smokier casinos that I have been in. We smelled like walking ashtrays the whole time we were there and we do not smoke. The only good thing I have to say about Caesars is that we did win some money there! But we will not be back!	
Nov 20 2009 	Choose your room carefully!	I traveled to Vegas with my mother, who is has Diamond status with the Harrah's hotels.At Caesar's Palace, this gives you access to your own registration desk &amp; other niceties, but we learned that it doesn't guarantee a decent room.They put us in the Colossus Tower, and the room was a real shock! Our two &quot;queen&quot; beds were really doubles, and the room was so small that there was ~6&quot; of space between the ratty couch by the window and the closest bed.But the beds themselves were just perplexing! One was okay, on par with what you'd expect to find in a decent Sheraton or Marriott - lots of padding between the mattress &amp; sheet, nice bedding, 3-4 pillows. The other bed, though, looked like a Motel 6 refugee: a thin sheet over a poor-quality mattress, and two skimpy pillows.So I tried to call the front desk, but the line just rang and rang. Tried the hotel operator, who stayed on the line until she could connect me to someone at one of the front desks. We were immediately moved to a room in the Augustus Tower, which was more in line with what we were expecting.The bellhop sent to transfer our luggage said he didn't know why they still rented out rooms in the Colossus &amp; Roman Towers (the oldest parts of the hotel). Once we saw our new room, I totally agree with him. It was like moving from a Comfort Inn to an upscale boutique hotel! Our new room was significantly larger, and included a seating area, a dining table with 4 chairs, two Actual Queen Beds with plenty of fluff &amp; pillows, mini-bar, flat-panel tv, and a luxurious bathroom: dual sinks, separate toilet room, jacuzzi tub, and glass-enclosed shower.Even the elevator lobbies and the hallway carpeting were a BIG step up in quality and appearance. If you visit the hotel's website, they don't even mention the Colossus or Roman Towers. The 360-view of a room in the Palace Tower is very similar to what we had in the nearby Augustus Tower. It really was as if we'd checked into 2 completely different hotels!Also, the spa is located in the Augustus Tower, and is well worth a trip. We both signed up for massages that were just wonderful, and we gave ourselves plenty of time to enjoy the &quot;Roman Baths,&quot; Saunas, etc., before &amp; after. Note: if you need a robe larger than ~2X, consider bringing your own. While we were checking in, another guest discovered that they didn't have enough larger-size robes to meet demand. It was a bit awkward for everyone!Caution: the price they charged us was a bit higher (~$30 each) than what we were quoted on the phone for our massages. When we said something, the clerk just shrugged his shoulders &amp; kept processing our payment. We didn't push, but I urge you to watch for that, in case it's a common practice.Long story short: location, location, location. Avoid the Colossus &amp; Roman Towers like the plague unless/until they have been completely overhauled &amp; renovated! Maybe they should just raze the buildings &amp; start over.	
Nov 19 2009 	Part of the Las Vegas experience	A stay at Caesar's Palace should be an essential part of a visit to Las Vegas but, be warned, compared to most of the other casinos, it is very expensive. We got a very good deal which included tickets to Bette Midler plus a nights stay for a reasonable price but we tried to book an extra night and found a fairly standard room to be $200 with no chance of a discount. In the end we booked across the road (literally) at Hurrahs and got a superior room for a quarter of the price!That said, the one night we had was a great little bit of luxury which added to the whole experience of being in Las Vegas. It was good to see the (wonderful) show and then just go up in the lift to bed. The room had all we could ask for and more with a great view and so was worth paying a bit over the odds just for one night. I think Caesar's Palace play too much on their name to keep prices artificially high, so be aware you can get much better deals in equally good accomodation elsewhere.	
