Aug 16 2009 	Not what it used to be - many better choices for the non-Harrahs junkie	I stayed 3 nights at Caesar’s at the conclusion of a 9-night business/pleasure trip to Vegas in June. The good: Beautiful, large room in the Augustus towerLovely spa and decent gymNext to overpriced forum shops (but a pretty mall)“Diamond” lounge access for semi-big-shot gamblers like I used to beConvenient locationHyakumi all-you-can-eat superb sushi/sashimiThe bad:Long lines unless you are a preferred gamblerRao’s restaurant is average and overpricedLong taxi and valet lines (again, short if you have “diamond” status)Bad odds on the video poker, slot machines, and only average BJ unless you play high limit.If you are given a free room, or somehow can get a good deal and stay in the lovely Augustus tower, this place MAY be worth a visit although there are better choices. As part of the Harrah’s chain lots of folks like to come here and keep their loyalty. But gambling odds are better elsewhere (try the Palms or the Wynn).I had dinner one night at Rao’s. Kind of like Buca di Beppo (a chain) without the super-oversized portions and way overpriced. Service was average. One great thing – all-you-can eat top shelf sushi at lunchtime for $28 or $38 at HyakumiHarrah’s clearly stacks the deck in favor of its frequent gamblers making short lines and free amenities available to them alone. But you have to gamble so much to get this status it will cost you thousands for these benefits.Spa charges $45 for the day (but only $25 for the diamond-card gamblers). All the luxury amenities but the layour somehow just didn’t “feel” right easy to get lost compared to other upscale spas I have been to.I had spent 2 nights at the Wynn/Encore (my favorite) with a friend, and then 5 nights at the Palazzo/Venetian for a conference (huge rooms and nice sportsbar) and I would recommend either over Caesars UNLESS you have the diamond card given to Harrahs big gamblers.Caesar’s used to be the best place in Vegas. Now as an independent tourist I’d choose Wynn/Encore, Palms, or Palazzo/Venetian – none of which part of the big chains. Or I’d go offstrip to the Marriott, RedRock or M resort. The Harrahs properties are for the birds.	
