 no satisfaction. I would suggest anyone staying anywhere else than Ceaser's Palace. Please do not go through this experience that I went through. We work hard for our money and they should too. Vegas is hurting for consumers like us to spend. I don't mind spending, but treat me like you would expect to be treated at the Mecca of gambling. I plan on writing them a letter and telling all what happened to me.	
Jun 13 2009 	A bit of ancient rome in the middle of Vegas	Once again it was time for me to head out to Vegas for a little relaxation and for this trip I chose to stay at Caesars Palace due to the fabulous rate I received for the Memorial Day holiday weekend. I wasn’t expecting it to be too crowded due to all the economic reviews I’ve been hearing, but I was sorely mistaken. Valet parking was PACKED when I arrived at 10PM and it was closed to all but Diamond and Seven Star members. I remembered there was valet parking in back by the parking garage and headed back there. No crowds and I zipped right in. The downside is the long walk to registration.When I arrived at the front desk there were only a couple of people ahead of me and it gave me time to figure out if I wanted to give the $20 “bribe” a shot. I was undecided and I always wonder if I’d come off looking like a fool. I waited till the last moment and decided the heck with it. The clerk was real friendly and he informed that as a Platinum member I could have stood in a quicker line (which actually wasn’t moving so quickly). As of April 1, 2009 I was no longer a Platinum member and had been busted back down to Gold due to my lack of gambling over the past 15 months. My online Harrah’s account has me listed as a Gold member, but my reservation had me pegged as a Platinum member – go figure &lt;shrug&gt;. It all worked to my benefit because he upgraded me to the 25th floor in the Palace Tower. Granted it’s NOT the nicest tower, but it was close to the pool and I had a half-way decent view of the strip. The walk to the Palace Tower from the front desk is a bit of a hike, but it’s not too horrible. I arrived at my room and was pleasantly surprised – the room had been recently updated (1+ year or so), decent sized, and the décor was modern with a touch of class. The room’s most unique feature is its dual marble bathroom, united by a walk-in shower and featuring an oversized spa tub. The room was clean upon my arrival and throughout my stay. The room came with the following amenities: LDC Television, bedside clock radio with CD player, &amp; MP-3 hook-up, Gilchrest &amp; Soames bath amenities, wet/dry mini bar, 2 waffle weave robes, and an in-room safe. One thing I did want to comment about was the great job the maids did in keeping everything clean because many of the hotel guests did their best to trash the place. Each day the hallway was spotless, but by the next morning people had trashed it. Garbage thrown on the floor, cigarette butts snubbed out on the wall and flicked to the floor, not to mention the amount of empty beer bottles tossed about. People, I realize you’re on vacation, but does that mean you have to act like a bunch of slobs???Off my soap box…As you can see from my pictures, there is a great deal of construction going on around the pool area which was a bit problemsome. I didn’t find the noise to be an issue, but the lack of chairs was a problem. I’m not sure if this is always an issue, but 15-20 minutes after the pool opened, all the chairs were taken. For the next few hours all you see are people walking around searching for a chair. During my stay, the hotel was extremely rigid in regards to when the pool opened. People were not allowed out into the pool area until 9:00 AM on the dot. Therefore, that meant people started forming a line at 8:30 AM. A word to the wise, forget about grabbing a towel right away. Go grab your chair and then head back to get a towel after most people have gone through the line or otherwise you’ll miss out on the prime real estate around the pool. Drink service was so so – I chose instead to walk up to the tiki bar and grab a brew rather than waiting for the waitress to come back around. The wait staff was working hard, they just couldn't keep up with all the demand.All in all I had a nice trip and would recommend Caesar’s Palace to many of my friends. It’s centrally located, nice pool area (when the construction is completed), nice restaurant and a large gaming area. Enjoy!!	
