May 26 2009	Avoid this hotel -- nothing but problems that the staff refuses to fix	I've been to Vegas hundreds of times. I've been going 2-4 times a year since I was a baby. This was the worst trip I've ever had, and it was all thanks to Caesar's Palace. My family had stayed there before about 4-5 years ago and we decided to stay there again this year b/c of a deal the hotel offered and b/c we wanted to take advantage of their nice pool area.We requested a room next to a family member's room. This was arranged months in advance, but when we got there we got moved from a room in the new, modern Augustus Tower to the completely out-dated, old-fashioned, poorly-furnished, horribly dark and dingy Roman Tower. They said our original room wasn't ready. When we complained we were told we had to pay for an upgrade even though they downgraded us without any notice at all! The room was facing another tower, the beds were smaller than any beds I slept in in European budget hotels (European hotels have smaller beds than American hotels, I have learned. Caesar's is the exception.) There was ZERO sunlight that entered the room, despite it being the beginning of a sunny, hot Vegas summer. There was only one light in the room and it took a lot of work to get it to function. The bathroom was remodeled, but only one of its 3 lights were functioning, making it very difficult to get ready in there. Everything was dirty, dark, and dingy. I should also mention at check-in that they said we had an envelope at another desk, but that desk said they didn't and treated us like we were crazy for asking. Two hours before checking out, we get a phone call that they had a gift card waiting for us. The gift card was for the hotel so we couldn't even use it! And it was a gift from a friend. What a waste!We tried getting out of the room and hanging out by the pool, but half the seats are reserved (pool guy told me you need to spend a half million before they can reserve seats for you). The pool chairs are all stacked in tight rows so you can't distance yourself from any other groups. This isn't a problem though since it's impossible to find any seats together. I got 4 seats b/c i went really early, but when I got out of the water I found that the pool guys had given my chairs to another group of people even though I had a beach bag, clothes, hats, magazines, and sunscreen covering them. Also, there was construction, and dust and debris got in the water and on my bathing suit. So now the room stunk and the pool stunk, so we went to the casino which was virtually empty. The lounges are all very dull and the only one that ever gets a crowd is the Shadow Bar. However, this may only be because it's so small 10 people constitute a crowd. There's no live music or any other kind of entertainment to enjoy while you drink or gamble. Also, the waitresses that worked the casino were very slow. I attribute this to the fact that they were understaffed and had to much ground to cover to work speedily and efficiently.The bellmen also were very slow. We waited over 30 min for one when we were checking out. They were severely understaffed, leading to delays and REALLY long lines at the bell desk.Also, don't expect extra towels, toiletries, or anything else because even if you request them and they say they'll send someone up they never do.Please avoid Caesar's Palace. It has gone down hill, the staff at the check-in/check-out desks are rude and unhelpful, and all the other areas of the hotel are understaffed. Instead, stay at Paris, Las Vegas. The rooms are much nicer, and if you don't get a remodeled room, the older rooms are a million times better than those at Caesar's.Caesar's will never see me or any of my friends and family again.	
