Apr 4 2009	They don't tell you this	My experience at Ceasers was not horrible, but we asked for a non-smoking room, which in most hotels is on a non-smoking floor. Apparently, this is not the case at Ceasers. We could smell cigarette smoke in our room...not stale, left-over, from a previous guest smoke, but like next door smoke coming through the vent or something. There are four boxes sitting on the dresser: chips, peanuts, cashews, poppycock and a Romance Package. There is no visible sign telling you this--the bellhop didn't tell us this--the front desk didn't tell us this--nor did the group we were with told us this, but if you even remove any of these boxes, you are charged for it. How do they know? There are sensors under them. Luckily, we called to find out what the deal was and if we were in fact charged for the things we touched, but didn't use. You have 30 seconds to look at it and put it back before you are charged. A small, single serve bag of Poppycock, nicely packaged in a fancy box was $10. Outrageous are the prices of this hotel! You pay big money for the rooms, which are nice, and then are so strengent about every little thing. There is no coffee pot in the room and if you use room service, be prepared to pay by the pot; $20. Don't order a soft drink, it's $4, but in the machine you can get it for $2.50. I wasn't impressed with the Shops at the Forum compared to the ones in some of the other hotel shops. I brought my computer so I could go online and research transportation and shows, etc. I could only get online with the hotel WiFi for $15. WIth the prices of everything else, they should provide this. Also, the ironing board stunk! No padding and very hard to iron on. They have a swimming pool, but there was so much construction, the jack hammers made laying by the pool impossible. I probably wouldn't stay here again.	
