Feb 12 2009 	Caesars is an attitude	The place has always had a little Sinatra swagger to it, reminiscent of Vegas in its halcyon days. It used to be unique, but other high-end properties like Mandalay Bay, Wynn, and the Venetian have caught up and even surpass it. She's kind of like Ingrid Bergman or Sophia Loren in their fifties -- still eminently presentable, but her best days are certainly behind her.The rooms are smart, comfortable, and well-appointed, though some of the older ones sport a view so poor, you'll want to keep the drapes closed. If you have a choice, opt for the Palace (first choice) or Augustus (second) Tower.By far the best amenity is still the pool. The drinks are expensive ($17 for a Caesars' Lemonade -- nicely spiked, of course), but you'll want to indulge. Service can be spotty at times -- truth be told, that millstone could be hung around all Harrah's properties -- but it is tends to be better than most. We have our favorite restaurants in Vegas, but it just so happens that none of them happen to be in Caesars, so even though we have stayed there at least a dozen times over the years, we can't express an informed opinion. Their spa and fitness club deserves a major-league demerit. It doesn't come close to measuring up to Mandalay Bay's -- and isn't much better than you find at Harrah's or the Rio -- but they have the audacity to charge for use of the shower facilities, even for their Diamond Club members. &quot;We're Caesars. We're better than you.&quot; The swagger can be endearing up to a point, but borders on the annoying.Caesars has grown almost by accident, and not according to any coherent plan. It has a few annoying quirks, such as a Diamond check-in area in a place where you can no longer drive to; after parking in the valet, you have to walk half-way around the property with luggage in tow. It's not a major concern for the casual traveler, although check-in lines for the average customer can be unduly extreme for a high-end property. Expect a long wait. A stroll through the Forum Shops is a delightful way to return from the Strip, but the only people who shop there have more money than sense. The Fashion Show Mall is just a short walk down the Strip, and a better place to indulge.	
Feb 10 2009 	On to be caesar	Firstly, can't believe I forgot to write review until now, most have been too busy telling everyone in person that we loved caesars!Stayed for two nights mid-week in November for our first trip to Vegas.Booked through travel agent, who booked through agency etc, so the hotel had problem tracking down our reservation initially. We appreciate these things happen, but the wonderful girl checking us in was very apologetic and got it sorted as quickly as possible. She also arranged an upgrade to the Augustus Towers overlooking the Bellagio Fountains for a knockdown price. The room, as mentioned by other posters is huge and the bathroom larger than many standard hotel rooms. So good we often felt bad for leaving. The rest of the hotel, if you can get around to all of it, is superb, and only regret is that we didn't have more time there.	
Feb 9 2009 	Inept Management Don't Stay at Caesars	I still find it unbelievable that I, and many others, had to wait over an hour to check in to Caesars Palace in Las Vegas on February 4, 2009. Hotel Management didn’t really seem to care that the line was extremely long. There was a hotel employee handing out water bottles, but when I asked for a cocktail or glass of wine I was denied. Would it have killed management to have the same employee pushing a cart with beer and wine for people waiting in line? When I finally got to the front of the line there was uncertainty related to whether I was going to get the room that I had a written confirmation for at the agreed upon price. The front desk employee told me that all of the rooms at “your price are sold out”, as if it was my fault. They asked me to pay extra to get into their next tier room. They still didn’t apologize for the hour-long wait. They didn’t offer a $50 hospitality credit to be used in a Caesars restaurant or bar for my time waiting in line. They were asking me for more money, which I refused. After a while they then “accommodated” me in another room, which was a normal room. It was as if Caesars had never checked in a large group of people before. It was amateur hour, and from speaking to other members of my group the line existed all day long. I thought I was in a Seinfeld episode.When the room was “cleaned” any dirty glasses or dishes were not removed from the room.The pool area was closed for renovation. Upon check out there was a $25 mini bar charge on my bill. I didn’t even open the door of the mini bar. As soon as I mentioned this, the charge was removed. Nice try Caesars, but I look at my bill.My advice to meeting planners, no matter where you stay, is to write in to the contract a penalty clause if the wait is over X number of minutes, the hotel owes each guest who waited longer than the agreed upon minutes a certain number of dollars. If the guest gets bumped to another hotel, their stay at the other hotel is free. In the age of computers there is no excuse to overbook a hotel and for there to be extra long check in lines. It is absurd. Caesars has clearly forgotten which industry they are in, it’s called hospitality. I would not recommend this hotel until it is sold to someone who cares about their guests.John PorrielloWethersfield, CT	
Feb 8 2009 	Long lines no coffee and upcharges for even the basics	Stayed Feb 2-6. Hoping for some comfort at a first class hotel after a chaotic day of airports and shuttle busses? Not even close. I arrived to find a line at the check-in that wrapped back and forth thru the lobby then down the hall to the shopping area. Waited over an hour. Velvet ropes were set up to manage the crowd - apparently this is a daily event. No apologies to the guests; no refreshments while waiting; no management to acknowledge that this was apalling for a $250+ per night &quot;first class&quot; hotel. And where was the bell staff to help guests to their rooms?For business travelers here for conferences, not for leisure, the hotel experience falls way short of expectations. Many of the basics that business travelers expect are absent . No newspapers for guest rooms. Internet access is $14.95 for 24 hours. It's $25 a day to use the fitness center. It's $5 for a kiosk to print your boarding pass. Good luck getting a cup of coffee in the morning. There are no in-room coffee machines, no free coffee in the lobby, and the coffee shop didn't open until 7 AM, too late for most conference goers. The only place I could get a cup each morning was in a bar in the casino area for $4 plus tip. When I asked the desk, they suggested that I order coffee via room serivce - but it would cost $11 plus $5 delivery fee plus 18% gratuity plus taxes.Everyone in my conference of 300+ people was buzzing about the check in debacle, and many of them waited the hour in line just to find that the hotel was oversold and they were bumped to another hotel. Even our keynote speaker, an expert on marketing of service businesses, commented about the hotel's shamefully bad customer service. I believe that Caesars Palace was once a fine hotel with a reputation for luxury, but clearly it has lost its way. I would never consider a return visit.	
